Prologue
"Please!'" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King looked down from his throne at his wife, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He scowled at that thought.
The little girl resembled her mother greatly: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, he had only sons until now.
Your only choices are to kill your child or send her back into nature. That is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He did it every time.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split in two, the North and the South. In the north, the non-magical realm. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastic representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two realms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South offered a truce.
Le Sud était acculé, et sa famille royale aurait fait n'importe quoi pour stopper le bain de sang. Ils proposèrent que leur unique princesse devienne la reine du Nord et porte un fils destiné à être le futur roi. Ensuite, le Sud se serait allié au Nord pour former un même royaume. Le Nord avait accepté, et la princesse Eirwen avait épousé le prince Akull.
"Je vous en supplie, mon altesse, en échange de la vie de mon enfant, faites ce que vous voulez de moi, enfermez-moi, bannissez-moi ou même, tuez-moi", plaida la reine Eirwen, en tenant fort son enfant dans ses bras.
Le roi de Glace baissa le regard sur sa femme, du dégoût dans les yeux. Peut-être, peut-être aurait-il pitié d'elle. Celle avec qui il vivait depuis vingt-deux ans, qui avait toujours pris soin de lui, dans ses heures les plus sombres, qui avait donné naissance à ses fils.
"Soit, l'enfant pourra vivre au palais", commença-t-il, arrachant un soupir de soulagement à sa femme. "Cependant", ajouta-t-il, "vous serez exécutée".
Le conseiller et la reine Eirwen elle-même partagèrent un regard horrifié. Elle baissa doucement le regard. "Oui Altesse", dit-elle en s'inclinant.
Le roi de Glace commanda au conseiller royal d'emmener l'enfant dans l'un des appartements vacants d'Eirwen. Une fois que ce fût fait, il ordonna aux gardes de conduire Eirwen jusqu'au site d'exécution, où tous les habitants du bourg pourraient assister au spectacle.
Alors que le gardes l'escortaient jusqu'au site, les habitants crièrent leur indignation en voyant leur seule reine, la plus gentille, sur le point d'être tuée. Certaines personnes pleuraient, d'autres hurlaient et essayaient d'attaquer les gardes, tandis que d'autres encore se demandaient ce qu'il se passait, mais tous étaient indignés.
"Libérez-la !"
"Pourquoi lui font-ils ça ?"
Alors qu'Eirwen approchait de la potence en bois, la personne la plus crainte du royaume fit son entrée. L'utilisateur du feu. L'ex-reine Eirwen allait être brûlée vive. Personne ne méritait une telle mort, pas même les criminels. C'était le châtiment le plus cruel à Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how Queen Eirwen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire burned the gallows, and a single tear rolled down the ex-queen's cheek.
"Survive, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds emanating from the farthest room to the left in the south wing of the still frozen palace. Passersby in the hallways wondered what was in that room, frightened of what could be inside. Gossip among the maids danced through the corridors. It was thought that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"They could not be more wrong," Ivory thought as she walked towards the south wing, while the aides scurried about whispering to each other. They have no idea what is in that room.
Certainly, these rumors applied to iel as well, because iel was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?"
Iel wondered if she would be invited in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory chuckled at that memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock comes from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I come in?" asked Ivory, remembering the time iel had done so without asking permission.
A loud knock came from inside. It seemed to mean yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear any sound coming from what was supposed to be an empty room, even though iel had been in this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but not unexpected. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were scattered about, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were strewn around. The room had no windows and very little light. It was colder here than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have descended within.
The girl there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her quilt, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook is it?" asked Ivory, sitting beside Kari on her bed.
